Conditionals are used to execute a block of code if a condition is true. The most common type of conditional statement in JavaScript is the "if" statement.

The "if" statement:
```javascript
if (/* condition */) {
  // code to be executed if the condition is true
}
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
let age = 18;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("You are old enough to vote.");
}
```

In the above example, the condition inside the parentheses evaluates to true because the value of the "age" variable is 18 or greater. Therefore, the code inside the curly braces is executed, and "You are old enough to vote." is logged to the console.

You can also include an "else" statement to execute a block of code if the condition is false:
```javascript
if (/* condition */) {
  // code to be executed if the condition is true
} else {
  // code to be executed if the condition is false
}
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
let age = 15;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("You are old enough to vote.");
} else {
  console.log("You are not old enough to vote.");
}
```

In the above example, the condition inside the parentheses evaluates to false because the value of the "age" variable is less than 18. Therefore, the code inside the curly braces after the "else" keyword is executed, and "You are not old enough to vote." is logged to the console.

You can also chain multiple "if-else" statements together using the "else if" keyword:
```javascript
if (/* condition */) {
  // code to be executed if the first condition is true
} else if (/* condition */) {
  // code to be executed if the second condition is true
} else {
  // code to be executed if all conditions are false
}
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
let age = 25;

if (age < 18) {
  console.log("You are not old enough to vote.");
} else if (age < 25) {
  console.log("You are old enough to vote, but not to rent a car.");
} else {
  console.log("You are old enough to vote and rent a car.");
}
```

In the above example, three conditions are checked. The first condition is false because the value of the "age" variable is greater than or equal to 18. The second condition is true because the value of the "age" variable is less than 25. Therefore, the code inside the curly braces after the second "if" statement is executed, and "You are old enough to vote, but not to rent a car." is logged to the console.

Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly. In JavaScript, there are three main types of loops: "for" loops, "while" loops, and "do-while" loops.

The "for" loop:
```javascript
for (/* initialization */; /* condition */; /* increment/decrement */) {
  // code to be executed during each iteration
}
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}
```

In the above example, the loop will iterate five times because the value of "i" starts at 0 and is incremented by 1 during each iteration until it reaches 4 (i.e., less than 5). Therefore, the numbers 0 through 4 are printed to the console.

The "while" loop:
```javascript
while (/* condition */) {
  // code to be executed during each iteration
}
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
let i = 0;

while (i < 5) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
```

In the above example, the loop will iterate five times because the value of "i" starts at 0 and is incremented by 1 during each iteration until it reaches 4 (i.e., less than 5). Therefore, the numbers 0 through 4 are printed to the console.

The "do-while" loop:
```javascript
do {
  // code to be executed during each iteration
} while (/* condition */);
```

Here's an example:
```javascript
let i = 0;

do {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

In the above example, the loop will iterate five times because the value of "i" starts at 0 and is incremented by 1 during each iteration until it reaches 4 (i.e., less than 5). Therefore, the numbers 0 through 4 are printed to the console. Note that the difference between a "do-while" loop and a "while" loop is that the code inside the "do" block is executed at least once, even if the condition is false.

You can also use the "break" and "continue" keywords to control the flow of the loop. The "break" keyword is used to exit the loop, while the "continue" keyword is used to skip the current iteration and move on to the next one.

Parameters are placeholders that represent the values passed in when a function is called. They help make a function more general by allowing it to operate on different inputs and allow the developer to write more flexible code. 

Arguments, on the other hand, are the actual values passed into a function when it is called. 

